If anybody wants a simple way to figure out the difference between transcription and translation, this helps me: DNA and RNA share the same language of nucleotides. They can write to each other, and just TRANSCRIBE information between them. DNA and proteins, however, don't share a language. DNA 'speaks' in nucleotides, and proteins 'speak' in amino acids. So they need RNA to TRANSLATE the information shared between DNA and the proteins.

From my 10th grade bio class to prepping for entering a hardcore research lab at university, crash course has always been there for me, thanks!

It is not true that a canonical TATA box is universal for all genes. Depending on the organisms and the definition of TATA box, it may be present on about 20% of the genes. A lot of genes may not even contain recognisable motifs of any sorts. We have no clues exactly how transcription is initiated on these promoters without core promoter motifs Also, Pol II does not start transcription directly downstream of the TATA, it starts at INR. TATA is 35 bp upstream of the start site. It is still a good video for learning transcription and translation!

Great video. I definitely use your entire Biology and Chemistry lines as one of my most dependable resources; it helps to have a conceptual understanding of the most important concepts before you delve deeper. I think a lot of people missed your disclaimer at the start of the season, or rather helpful observation...  You can pause these videos at any point, repeat them, or add CC.  Guys, I get that he talks fast, but that's an intentional design of most of the Crash Course videos in the first place. Don't expect these videos to solve your immediate and specific problems on their own. These are intended as a tool, not an entire repository of knowledge. Need a textbook? Use the internet. Or internet textbooks. (e.g. http://open.umn.edu/opentextbooks/BookDetail.aspx?bookId=244)

They basically have the ability to turn prokaryotic genes on or off (Only in prokaryotes though). An example of this would be how your body reacts when you need to digest lactose. When your body takes in food, it needs to know how to break it down. To do this, it checks for instructions. Think of it like going down a checklist, with each item on the checklist being a gene. If it comes to a gene that is turned on, then it will follow those instructions. So how does your body able to control which genes are on and which genes are off? So that it goes to the right instructions and doesn't go somewhere else? It uses active repressors. In fact, every gene is by default turned off. Every gene has an active repressor on it, blocking the gene's instructions. So how do you 'deactivate' the repressor, so that when you need the instructions you can get them? Well, each repressor can be turned off when exposed to something specific (if you need multiple instructions, then that 'something' can turn off multiple repressors). Once the repressor is made inactive due to this new item, the instructions can be sent. For example, lactose intolerance. You don't want your body to try and digest everything like it was lactose, right? It'd just end up burning a hole in your stomach...so it blocks the genes that would give those instructions. What happens when it actually needs to digest lactose? Well it just so happens that the repressor controlling those instructions is made inactive when exposed to lactose. So there you go. Eat a hamburger? It doesn't have lactose, so the repressor is unaffected and stays hooked onto the gene so that your body doesn't give the wrong instructions. Drink a glass of milk? Since lactose has now entered your body, it reacts with the repressor to deactivate it. This turns the gene back on, which tells your body how to digest the lactose, and everything runs smoothly. Tada!  Hence why lactose intolerance is a disorder that is passed on from person to person. You don't have the gene which has those instructions on how to digest lactose. Your body doesn't know what to do with it. Hope this helps Guardian! (Yes, I see your Destiny icon. Is Titan your main class? I'm personally more of a Hunter myself.)
